etymologies: early 17th century; earliest use found in William Watson (?1559–1603), Roman Catholic priest and conspirator. From post-classical Latin immatriculat-, past participial stem of immatriculare from im- + matriculare

definitions: matriculate in various senses, especially to enrol (a person) at a university; usually in passive. Also without object: = "matriculate".

notes.text: Now chiefly with reference to Germany or in German-speaking contexts.
